📈 Russian economy forecast has been improved

IMF has stated that it has increased estimates of Russian economy growth from –2.3% contraction to 0.3% growth in 2023 despite a broad array of Western sanctions.

The IMF attributes this improvement to Russia finding new clients outside the West by redirecting trade from sanctioning to non-sanctioning countries. Activity of Russian defense industrial complex was one of the main contributors for projected growth.

These are good news, as we know that Western forecasts never favor Russia. Last year they forecasted collapse of Russian economy, then they stated that it will not return to growth until second half of 2020s, then it was 2024 and now it has already happened.

It looks like IMF reluctantly acknowledged amazingly quick recovery of Russian economy to add credibility to its other forecasts, such as the one concerning Europe. Yes, you heard it right, they forecast that European economy will grow in 2023. Despite it having far deeper problems than Russia. 

The thing is that Russia had to find customers for its export products, which are in very high demand. This was not really a problem as long as two thirds of the world didn’t join Western sanctions or simply ignored them. 

European problem is different, they need to find resources, especially energy. Amid looming energy crisis and soaring prices that are expected to come this year when Chinese reopening gains momentum, their chances to get a good deal are slim. 

For now, Europe is still living on Russian resources, despite all of their nice words. They are getting them from intermediary countries while some are coming directly from Russia. There is physically no way to replace Russian supplies and maintain European industry competitive, so all growth forecasts are likely to be artificial. 

There is a fundamental flaw in IMF estimations of economic growth. They estimate this growth in US dollars, and it is no longer a stable currency as it once used to be. 

Moreover, the rate of USD and EUR is greatly inflated and as these currencies are slowly but steadily losing relevance for international trade, estimates in these currencies are no longer objective. More objective are estimations based on purchasing power of currency and not on its market rate to USD. 

If we estimate things by purchasing power parity, we’ll see that Russian economy is actually twice stronger than it seems to the West, and so its growth is far better than anyone could guess. For reference, while market exchange rate is around $1 = 70 rubles, purchasing power rate is under 30 rubles per dollar.

Fortunately for Russia, dollar rate has little impact on its economy and influences only foreign trade. As Russia is readjusting its import-export flows, higher dollar rate means that Russia earns more money through export and can afford to import more goods, which translates into lower consumer prices. 

A fun fact, prices on modern notebooks in Russia fell by 25 percent since last October due to competition of parallel import and Chinese manufacturers trying to enter the lucrative Russian market. So, Russia is fine. Can’t say that of Europe.

💰More billions to Ukraine — plague feast continues

According to Bloomberg, IMF is currently considering another $16 billion aid package for Ukraine.

The Fund's program will require fulfillment of a number of conditions, and the first disbursement may come as early as April.

Ukraine is already the third highest borrower of the IMF. Its debt has been mounting higher and higher for years, and in a few months after Russian SMO started the country got technically bankrupt. Ukraine’s creditors have suspended repayment until the end of this year, or else the country would have been unable to meet its obligations.

Maybe naïve Ukrainians keep thinking that someone will write off or cover their debts, but it is too much of wishful thinking. Money drives the West, and they are not a charity to give this money for free. So yes, future generations of Ukrainians will still pay. 

Meanwhile, the current government is enjoying its feast in the time of plague and is asking for more and more tools of war and money to pay its current bills. When a country cannot service its debt, it becomes dependent on its creditors, and Kiev regime turned Ukrainians into eternal serfs of the West.

One could compare Ukrainian elites with gamblers who have already lost everything and are now going deep in debts in desperate attempts to win something. While they really look this way, they are not so stupid. 

Zelensky and his team are just trying to drain as much money as they can from “Project Ukraine” to enjoy safe and comfortable retirement somewhere in Miami together with other former leaders of Maidan. 

Despite Zelensky playing role of a hero president, neither he nor anyone else can save Ukraine from military defeat and complete bankruptcy. It’s highly likely that Ukrainian government will completely change when Russia ends its special military operation, and it’s also highly likely that new Ukrainian government will face very hard choices with regard to debts made by Zelensky & Co. 

I don’t think that there is anyone left in Ukraine who believes fairly tales about EU entry “in just a couple years”, huge EU subsidies and life without poverty. Europe has its own problems and it’s more likely that in a couple years many Europeans will live like Ukrainians and not vice versa. 

So, this hypothetic future Ukrainian government will have only one way out of debt — pay it with assets, and land is the only liquid asset Ukraine has. West Ukraine will probably be enough, so this part of Ukraine will surely get to EU as a part of Poland… or maybe even Germany, who knows how things will change after a few more AFU defeats.

In recent years far right parties have gained some momentum in Scandinavia, most notably in Sweden. 

Paludan’s movement does not enjoy popularity at home and that is the reason why he chose neighboring Sweden for his performances — Stockholm has more loyal audience. Populist right party “Swedish Democrats” is a part of the ruling coalition of Sweden and a large part of its members have strong anti-Muslim views. Sweden is becoming an arena of increasing ethnic and religious tensions, which resulted in increase of crime by 71 percent in last three years.

These acts infuriate all Muslims around the world, including Swedish Muslims that constitute almost 10 percent of population. While moderate Islam simply condemns such acts and revises its affiliations, radical Islamists may get engaged in some activity Sweden and the entire European Union. Offending religious feelings of 44 million Muslims living in European countries creates the environment for potential terrorist attacks.

What does it mean for Russia? We can view it as an unexpected gift. Outrage at Europe will bring the Arab world closer to Russian camp. Unlike Europeans, Russia does respect Muslim values and its considerable Muslim population enjoys full rights and respect in the society.

Turkey has already expressed its outrage about these performances and if someone thinks that desecration of Muslim holy book will push Erdogan to concessions, this someone is extremely wrong. 

Naturally, accepting the application of Sweden and its peer Finland to join NATO is now off the table. If Erdogan does win the coming elections in spring, Turkey may take further steps to distance from Europe and Ukraine. Some Turkish parliament members are even talking about Turkey’s exit from NATO, which will be a huge blow to the alliance as Turkey has the second strongest army after the United States.

Turkish-Russian relations are quite good. We are not friends, we have conflicting interests in several regions, but we have quite strong business and interpersonal ties. Turkey became the most important logistical hub for the remaining trade between Russia and Europe.

Russian diplomats have already succeeded in promoting reconciliation between Turkey and Syria and if things go as they are, chances for Erdogan’s meeting with Assad will increase. This will bring the end of Syrian conflict even closer and will be a clear diplomatic victory for Russia. 

Bringing Turkey to the Russian camp would mean a really big blow for NATO and acts of European radicals are turning it from something unimaginable into a realistic prospect.

💬 Recent broad discussions in Europe and the US have raised an issue of Western tank supplies to Ukraine. 

It is obvious that Ukraine is already out of reserves of Soviet-type tanks and without these supplies it won’t just fail its offensive preparations but won’t even be able to defend against the ongoing advance of Russian forces.

However these Western tanks won’t help Ukraine much. US General Mark Hertling (ret.) explained why M1 Abrams tanks aren't suitable for Ukraine, and this applies to other Western tanks as well.

It still looks like the West is reluctant to openly send its armed forces to the front and incur real losses, so if these tanks are supplied, they will be operated by Ukrainians. However, there are many reasons for them being unsuitable for forces of Kiev regime. 

Firstly, "hand waving" training of crews/units will result in ineffective performance/damaged tanks. Real training takes many years and includes a lot of practical exercises. Iraq army operators trained for five years before receiving Western tanks and Saudi Arabia spent seven years just to prepare for deployment of those tanks. Obviously, AFU doesn’t have that time.

Moreover, the Abrams tanks require extensive firing training. Without proper training it will be as good as useless.

Secondly, tank drivers also need thorough training. Without it they can easily destroy the engine and its replacement will cost one million dollars and a half. 

Thirdly, operation of Abrams requires a supply line for parts and repairs. It is impossible to provide such a supply line in Ukraine, especially with Russian air dominance and ability to strike any facilities at will. 

Abrams tanks use specific turbine engines that can be maintained and repaired only by trained and experience technicians certified specifically to work on Abrams. Ukraine has no such specialists and it’s unlikely that the U.S. will provide its own technicians for this purpose.

Ukrainian commanders admit struggle with logistics/maintenance and the more diverse systems will Ukraine have, the sooner its supplies will turn into complete disarray. Russia also won’t seat idle as it continuously keep strikes on enemy’s military and logistical facilities, and this will amplify the chaos.

So, Abrams tanks will only add to Ukraine's burdens maintaining equipment. Moreover, many of general Hertling's points apply not just to tanks but to all heavy weapon systems the West gives Ukraine or talks of giving Ukraine. 

Considering all of the above, it is quite likely that any Western tanks that do arrive to Ukraine won’t go east of Lviv. What will they do in Lviv? Ask Radoslaw Sikorsky.

⚡️NATO plans — look beyond Ukraine

NATO plans to increase production of ammunition to support Ukraine and requests alliance members to increase military expenses to at least 2% GDP.

Mircea Geoană, NATO Deputy Secretary General announced the need to significantly increase production of weapons and ammunition for Ukraine and NATO’s own defense. He also mentioned that NATO countries must continue increasing their military expenses and that 2% GDP is not a desired value but a minimum, base level.

This way the alliance acknowledges that munition plants of NATO countries are unable to fulfil the demands of Ukraine in its conflict with Russia. While the West regularly speaks about Russian shortages of ammunition, it seems they are just projecting their own problems on Russia.

Russia has no problems with artillery shells or any other ammunition. It may be surprising to many, but Russian defense industry currently produces more high caliber shells than US military industrial complex. 

Western military experts continuously note that Russia spends more artillery shells than Ukraine. Ukraine is already close to ammunition shortage and globally praised US defense industry is unable to cover this shortage. Moreover, they won’t be able to do it even after planned expansion of production capacity by 2024-2025. 

When they talk about significant increase of capacities, they don’t mean it will happen in one day. It will take at least 1-2 years, and AFU capabilities during that period will be greatly restricted. 

Russia is not planning to extend the SMO for years or decades and no token aid from the West will save Kiev regime from the fate it deserved. 

As for NATO, they better stop planning expansion of weapon industry and acknowledge reality. It’s time to stop supporting crazy neo-Nazis and start talking to Russia about new security framework. 

Although NATO’s military industry has limited capacity, the North Atlantic Alliance is still very strong. However, it didn’t start open war against Russia and will not do it because it will mean inevitable retaliation strike.

Without direct interference of NATO their military aid to Ukraine will not save Zelensky’s regime. It is unlikely that NATO will be able to increase the production capacity before Russian SMO ends. 

However, it’s too early to relax. NATO leaders are not fools and if they are increasing production, it means that they are preparing for future conflicts. Maybe those won’t be conflicts with Russia, but Russia should not rely on that. 

Russia needs to look beyond Ukraine. Ending SMO as soon as possible is the primary and most important objective, but the end of SMO will not mean the end of conflict between Russia and NATO. New Cold War is inevitable.

🪖 Shifting the balance 

Recent Russian advances near Soledar and Artemovsk contradict “Ukrainian offensive momentum” narrative and ruin its image in the collective West. Real achievements are the best thing to break fake narratives. And the real thing is that Ukraine has not captured a single town in battle. 

Russian operations are consistent with the demilitarization objective for the special military operation. Desperate AFU attempts to defend hopeless position result in immense losses of manpower and equipment.

Artemovsk and Soledar are fortified cities along one of Ukraine’s last defensive lines in the Donbass region. Fall of that defense line will open Russia a path to liberate all of Donbass. Therefore, Kiev regime does not have much choice other than keep throwing demoralized and poorly trained forces into the cauldron. They are waiting for Western military aid hoping that it can turn the tide but Western military aid is not a panacea. 

The West is indeed announcing plans to send main battle tanks to Ukraine including Challenger 2 and Leopard 2 tanks. However, these tanks use different ammunition & both require an additional crew member (loader) increasing training demands for Ukrainian forces. 

The large variety of equipment the West is sending will create additional burdens for Ukrainian forces without any notable benefit. Tanks and artillery pieces are not supplied in hundreds and don’t even make up for Ukrainian losses. 

Moreover, Western main battle tanks have proven to be vulnerable to (Russian-made) modern anti-tank weapons even under relatively ideal conditions. When driven by poorly trained disorganized forces they will just become easy target.

Ukrainian forces will be going into battle without sufficient artillery or air cover and facing off against Russian forces reinforced with an additional mobilized men, new defenses and an influx of new weaponry. 

Kiev propaganda continues spreading their fake stories but they are no longer able to hide their losses. No more enthusiasm, nothing new or exciting in their speeches.

What will happen next? Western sponsors keep poking Kiev regime to launch offensives and show progress. However, Kiev doesn’t really have what it takes for a successful offensive. Losses in Soledar and Artemovsk areas have ruined those chances. 

Foreign mercenaries are willing to provide training and guidance but they are not willing to die for Ukraine, so Ukraine has to force mobilize random people on the streets to fill the ranks on defense. Moreover, offensive operations involve far greater casualties. Something to think about.

Kiev regime now faces some choices on the front. They can keep holding desperate positions in Artemovsk by sending more and more cannon fodder. They can fall back to next defense line and use all reserves to strengthen it. Or they can fall back, man the defenses, scrape everything they have and prepare an offensive. Neither option looks too promising. 

Of course, they also have another option – return to negotiations without any preconditions. That would be rational choice but rational thinking is not something associated with Zelensky regime.

💥 Results of 2022 – geopolitical struggle

In geopolitics 2022 has been a year of big changes and future historians might even view it as the year when the Western world order was challenged. Of course, Russian Federation was in the center of all ongoing events. 

January saw last Russian attempts to maintain peaceful coexistence and mutually profitable trade with the West. Further plans of NATO expansion were not tolerable and around that time Russian leadership felt that Ukrainian conflict will never get resolved without real Russian intervention and made the decision to run a special military operation. 

Russian request to guarantee non-expansion of NATO and create a new security infrastructure was dismissed and this dismissal probably became the last drop that turned the scales. While the collective West still had an option to refrain from interference and acknowledge Russian security interests in its direct vicinity, they have chosen the other path. 

The option of attacking Russia directly was off the table from the very beginning. However, Russian adversaries still remembered their success in destruction of the USSR and so they started another project aimed to weaken Russia economically, incite internal unrest and install their own puppet government. 

This manifested in a full-scale information war and economic war against Russia. Unprecedented level of sanctions resulted in withdrawal of most Western companies from Russia and termination of economic ties that lasted for decades. A slander campaign of the scale that was never seen before followed the economic pressure. 

However, the plan did not work. Russia managed to preserve its economic strength and its internal unity through well calculated measures. The West failed to cripple Russia economically and did not manage to fool Russian people except a negligible minority that fled the country. 

Moreover, Russian geopolitical weight in the world has greatly increased. Three fourths of the world are now looking at Russia and cheering for it to succeed in its geopolitical stand against the new world order established by the collective West. 

Russia has offered the world an alternative vision of the future instead of US-dominated consumer society with inherent inequality and exploitation of the weak by the strong. Russian President has officially stated that while the time of unipolar world is gone. 

21st century will be the century of Asia and Russia has already started its geopolitical turn from the rotting West to the rising East. Russian partnership with Asian countries is growing stronger with every passing month and petty games and slander attempts of the collective West will not be able to change it.

▪️On December 30th Vladimir Putin had traditional end-of-year video conversation with Chinese leader Xi Jingping and noted that Russian-Chinese relations are a perfect example of cooperation between large countries in 21st century. Russian President has noted that Russia and China have similar views on causes, progress and logics of global geopolitical transformation in the environment of unprecedented pressure and provocations by the West and defend not only their own interests but interests of all proponents of truly democratic world order and the right of countries to freely choose their own way. 

Together, Russia and China have all chances to establish the new world order. Inevitable Russian victory in Ukrainian conflict will embolden more countries to challenge the West-dominated world order and firmly stand on the Russian side. 

So let’s wish for the coming year to be remembered as the year of Russian victory and emergence of a global coalition of sovereign countries united by common objective — to live their own way without any foreign interference.

⬛️ According to recent report in Financial Times, almost 90 percent of surveyed economists expect that energy shortage will trigger eurozone contraction in 2023. 

Experts acknowledge that European economy is already in recession and it will intensify next year even more. High inflation and energy shortage push a strong pressure on EU industry, salary increases are falling short behind inflation, consumer demand falls and this is triggering a chain reaction that will manifest most noticeably in the coming year.

This report greatly contradicts optimistic statements of European politicians, which in fact turn to be quite void. This year Europe managed to reduce its energy consumption by 20 percent. But how was it achieved? Despite widely publicized household energy-saving measures, they account just for a tiny bit of energy consumption. Expensive transition to energy-efficient technologies also helped a tiny bit, but the lion’s share of energy saving is due to reduced consumption by European industry. 

Plants are reducing production, businesses close, companies see lower profits and are looking for ways to cut costs. Facing much higher energy costs and falling demand they are virtually forced to “optimize” labor costs, resulting in even more unemployment, even lower demand and so on.

For many decades European industry was considered innovative and competitive, for many years European income level was considered relatively high as compared to most other countries. We knew that a good part of high income was compensated with high costs of living, but we thought that aside for that best European countries are really demonstrating outstanding competence in running their economies. 

However, it turned out that all of this was just an illusion and the real foundation of European competitiveness was very simple — cheap Russian energy that it was getting from USSR and later Russia. With few exceptions such as Norway that has its own energy resources, the competitiveness of Europe was dependent on Russian energy and it was an incredible level of dependence that nobody could even imagine.

Energy prices impact industry not only directly through the energy it consumes but also indirectly through increased prices on components and higher costs of storage and transportation. Even slight increase in energy prices has multiplicative effect on manufacturing costs of final product. 

Now just think, Europe now pays 2-4 times more for its energy. Consumer sector is subsidized, but subsidies won’t work for industry. Paying billions to subsidize companies and getting back millions in taxes does not sound like a plan. It can work for a short period, but European pockets are not endless and the crisis spiral is already in motion. 

In face of inevitable increase of global demand for energy, the Eurozone sees itself in completely uncompetitive position. The euro bubble will sooner or later burst out, and European authorities can do little to prevent it.

Still, it can be a good sign for Europe as well. When Europe shifts to survival mode, there is a good chance that hardships will finally open the eyes of European people and they will kick out globalist talking heads out and elect new generation politicians out of more reasonable people.

After recent vague statements of Ukrainian leadership about some “peace plans” Western media is once again circulating the idea that Russian President Vladimir Putin asks for negotiations and discusses guarantees that Russia could give to Ukraine and the West that it “will not repeat its aggression”. Nothing could be further from what is really going on. Russian leader is not asking for negotiations, he is just saying that Russia is open to diplomatic resolution of the conflict.

▪️Russia has been ready to accept Ukrainian surrender ever since the beginning of the special operation, nothing changed here. Ukraine knows Russian terms and whatever is the picture that Western MSM try to create, this picture has little to do with reality. And the reality has been obvious from the very beginning.

As for guarantees, yes, it’s a hard question. Probably everyone in Russia remembers the story of Minsk Agreements that were never implemented while their supposed European guarantors have acknowledged that their objective was just “win time to arm Ukraine”. So, it is highly unlikely that Russia will agree to that sort of deal and step on the same rake once again. 

This time Russia will require permanent solution and more serious guarantees strengthened by immediate actions that have to be done before anything is signed. Yes, everyone needs guarantees. Ukraine may also need some guarantees, and Ukraine may even get those guarantees but it first has to make sure that the story of last eight years will never repeat.

▪️From Russian side it is obvious that Russia will not accept any guarantees by Europe. The memory of European betrayal is too fresh. Guarantees will have to come from the United States in form of written binding agreements and they must include China as another guarantor to make sure US don’t forget their promises right when the ink gets dry.

▪️As for Ukraine, the initial Russian proposal was absolutely fair. If Russia, US and any willing European countries guarantee territorial integrity and safety of Ukraine, if Ukraine is fast-tracked to EU, it should feel safe enough to demilitarize. The only thing Russia objects to is any kind of NATO membership and NATO bases in new Ukraine in any form.

Demilitarization is obviously needed. As it stands now, Ukraine has the second largest army in Europe after Russia. Armed with NATO weapons, fielding NATO military equipment, using NATO air defense systems. Even before the conflict Ukraine was excessively militarized and its military was much larger than needed for a country of this scale.

▪️So, what will make Ukraine safe from Russian intervention in future? Constitutional amendments establishing neutrality of Ukraine and granting equal rights, freedom of speech and freedom of speaking native language to all its citizens.

▪️This kind of deal is the only deal that Ukraine can get. Territorial issue has to be resolved once and for all. Ukraine should not expect any better terms but they surely can get worse. Current terms are already worse than those offered in spring.

The idea that Ukraine has the right to demand something is misleading. Defeated country cannot demand anything. It can only try to minimize its losses.

Russia has finally responded to oil price restrictions implemented by European Union and the collective West. Yesterday President Putin has signed a decree that prohibits sale of oil and oil products under supply contracts that directly or indirectly specify any restrictions of prices. 

⬜️ The decree comes into effect on February 1st and will first apply only to supplies of oil. The government of the Russian Federation was ordered to prepare the timeframe and the list of oil products that will also be subject to new restriction.

While the oil part was expected and has been previously announced, adding oil products to the restriction list means that Russian response is very real and that these measures are not just for the show. 

⬜️ This is important because it shows that Russia won’t circumvent its own prohibition by supplying new products like “crude oil mix” in compliance with the price cap. The price cap is simply being dismissed. Russian oil exporters won’t be able to circumvent the decree for profit. 

Moreover, the decree refers to contracts, so any countries willing to buy Russian oil or oil products won’t be able to acknowledge the price cap even if the contract price falls within its limits. 

⬜️ It should have been clear from the very beginning that Russia will not accept any kind of restrictions. Western sanctions restrict shipment and insurance but Russian partners in Asia are already working on creation of alternative shipping and insurance schemes. 

OPEC countries and other oil exporters have already spoken against the price cap and this means that at the very least they will support Russia by reselling its oil and at the very best they will help Russia and its Asian partners with alternative shipment insurance structure that will be completely independent from the West.

Virtually all oil and gas exporters are outraged with European ideas to establish price restrictions. Even U.S. companies have spoken against the idea. 🔴 The problem of American military industrial complex

Myths of immense capacities of U.S. military industrial complex turned out to be somewhat exaggerated. As it turns out, their existing capacities are not sufficient to sustain the Ukrainian army for much longer and they can potentially crank up production to the required level only in 2025.

▪️ While in times of World War 2 and even the Cold War U.S. arms industry was working on very different principles. It was a largely state-subsidized industry that was not that much profit-oriented and that used traditional methods prioritizing production capacity. In last decade of the 20th century most of these enterprises switched to “efficiency theories” that were borrowed by the West from Japan, such as Kaizen, Six Sigma, etc. 

Efficient production means that you produce only what you can sell and you cut down costs of maintenance of industrial facilities and equipment that you don’t need. Cutting down costs and avoiding excessive production is the way to achieve biggest profits. You can produce a bit more counting on future projections, but you will not produce ten times more than you need. 

▪️ Besides, in recent decades most orders to American military industrial complex were about the need to support overseas operations of US military and this involved specific orders for many specific types of weapons that were good for expedition forces but are not suitable for a conflict like Ukrainian. 

While U.S. military industrial complex is tightly integrated, it consists of hundreds and thousands of companies and virtually all complex items of weaponry and equipment require cooperation of many entities. It means that when U.S. faced the need to arm Ukraine, it could not just go and start production. 

They needed to place orders, run tenders, select suppliers. Then those suppliers had to return their old manufacturing equipment to service or build new facilities and production lines, find suppliers of components, and so on, and so on. Effectively the U.S. has to create many production facilities from scratch and with unclear prospects of their future use.

▪️ Some articles such as HIMARS units and missiles will still be in demand after the Ukrainian conflict ends, but items like Javelins and Stingers are already quite obsolete and it is unlikely that they will be needed anywhere else.

So, while the U.S. military industrial complex enjoys the allocated money and prepares to ramp up production in next couple years, they cannot but think about possible futility of their work if the conflict ends before that.

❗️By the way, those multi-billion numbers of military aid to Ukraine are not so real and not so huge as it seems. The thing is that they are accounting this aid at sale prices. Production costs and sales price are very different. 

US budget pays US military factories and defense contractors their sale price instead of covering their costs of production. Of course, Ukraine will cover the sales price or rather the West will try using frozen Russian assets to cover the sales price if the conflict will end with anything but Russian victory.

What does it all mean for Russia? It’s not worth underestimating the enemy. However, as U.S. industrial capacity will be fully deployed only around 2024-2025, Russia must use the remaining time window to end the conflict in its favor.

❓How can Russia justify the retreat from Kherson after referendums? According to Russian laws, Kherson is in Russia.

 🔷Russian Ministry of Defense justifies it with its desire to avoid inevitable losses if it tried to hold the city. However, this point is what worries a lot of Russians, especially Russians in new territories. In fact, Russia did concede a Russian city without even trying to hold it. If it was formally Ukrainian, it would be much less of a problem.
There are many versions of possible reasons for that decision, there are many rumors in the air.

🔷However, it’s anyway a big PR loss and a big hit on government ratings. Referendum did changed things and the order for retreat does undermine the results of this referendum. Moreover, the very objective of running the referendum so early was to assure the people of new regions that Russia will defend them. Yes, civilians were evacuated from Kherson, but this still doesn’t look good considering the above objective.

🔷Nevertheless, there is no reason for Russians to panic or accuse the government of deliberate concessions. The decision was well thought and we’ll eventually see that it was wise. If we put PR aside, it makes perfect sense from military point of view. Russia stabilizes the front and stops Ukrainian offensive freeing its own forces to be used in other areas. Russia is still winning the war of attrition and still has good chances to see Ukrainian capitulation without taking heavy losses in manpower.   

🔷Saving lives of Russian soldiers is indeed a good purpose and a good reason for retreat. Slowly advancing Ukrainian forces greatly outnumbered Russian defenders in Kherson and their artillery was able to hit Russian supply routes. It wasn’t worth sacrificing soldiers for a city that couldn’t be held risking total cut-off and destruction of the entire defending force. Russia is not Ukraine and is not abandoning its fighters to die. 

 🔷Unfortunately, retreat inevitably means that any people who refused evacuation from Kherson are likely to become victims of war crimes by Ukrainian nationalists. We can expect more mass murders and attempts to frame Russia in further attempts to promote the cause of Kiev regime.
For now, Russians just have to wait a little more. New troops will arrive to the front, forces from Kherson will regroup to other areas and inevitable Russian counteroffensive will follow. Meanwhile, continued missile strikes will disrupt Ukrainian supplies and their ability to move troops, while their sponsors will come back in another month demanding for more success.

🔷This is not over. Kiev government will not negotiate a ceasefire or truce and treaty unless pushed by the U.S., but the U.S. seems to be fine with the way things are going and will literally fight Russia to the last Ukrainian. Only physical destruction of Ukrainian ability to fight will bring some decisive results and may force the other side to talk.  

 🔷So yes, it was a hard decision and undeniable loss of face for Russia. However, Russians don’t say farewell to Kherson, they just say “See you later”

Republican victory and Ukraine funding prospects

🇺🇸November elections in the U.S. are already over and although it seems that Republican did win majority in Congress, it was not an overwhelming victory or expected “red wave”. The Senate breakdown is unclear and it is quite likely that Democratic party will maintain their control. How will these results impact the Ukrainian conflict?

🔷Despite some Republican slogans about ending U.S. military and financial aid to Ukraine, Russia had no high hopes about the results of the elections. Some signs indicate that Russia did favor the Republicans this time and even withheld announcement of withdrawal from Kherson city in Ukraine until the voting ended.

🔷Nonetheless, Russia knows that the majority of U.S. Republicans just as the majority of U.S. Democrats are not Russian friends and will not do anything that will look as a favor to Russia. U.S. support to Ukraine depends more on physical constraints and situation in U.S. economy than on the party controlling the House. 

🔷If any changes are expected about U.S. aid to Ukraine, those are changes about accountability. Both Republicans and Democrats are concerned about rumors of U.S.-supplied weapons ending on black market and on very high level of corruption in the AFU. 

🔷According to recent reports, the U.S. are now planning to supply Ukraine with some older stocked weaponry because they are out of reserve stock for newer models and are not able to replenish this stock quickly and provide the necessary ammunition, production ramp will take from 1 to 3 years. 

🔷That said, with Ukrainian counter-offensive soon to be stalled on the Dnieper and stabilization of the front line, further development of the situation will depend on Russian ability to disable enemy equipment. Neither Europe, nor the U.S. are willing to make their industry work solely to supply Ukraine and Ukrainian army. Ukraine’s own arms industry has very limited capacity and is mostly used to repair damaged tanks and vehicles. 

🔷This means that at some point of time foreign sponsors will no longer be able to replenish Ukraine’s losses, be it U.S. Republicans, U.S. Democrats or whoever else. The only thing Russia has to do is to outlast Ukraine and win the war of attrition and it looks like this is the tactics chosen by the Russian Ministry of Defense for this very reason.

🔷While the issue with military aid is clear, the issue with financial aid is still on the table. Ukrainian budget deficit is counted in billions, Ukraine’s chances to repay debts are very slim and the U.S. are not a charity fund.

Retreat from Kherson

🔷On November 9th Russian Minister of Defense Sergei Shoigu has ordered Russian forces to retreat from the city of Kherson to prepared defense positions on the left coast of Dnieper. The Minister said that life and health of Russian servicemen are always a priority.

🔷This order followed report of General Surovikin who stated that while Russian Armed Forces successfully repeal all Ukrainian attempts of offensive in the area and have inflicted heavy casualties on the enemy, AFU keep launching strikes on schools, hospitals and civilian population of Kherson, which is currently being evacuated across the Dnieper. Surovikin stated that all civilians willing to evacuate have been evacuated and over 115,000 citizens have been transported to safety.

❓What will this mean to the course of special operation? From military point of view it will stabilize the front line and allow Russian forces to concentrate on other areas avoiding losses in an attempt to hold Kherson with supply lines across the Dnieper being in the range of Ukrainian artillery. 

☝️From PR point of view this retreat poses a serious problem. It is going to become a media victory for Ukraine. Although this retreat was not forced and is not a result of any military defeat, the West will surely present it as a big victory for Ukraine and will demonstrate Ukrainian sponsors that their money is not being spent in vain. It is unlikely that it will work for long, but Ukraine will try to use it as much as possible.

🔷However, this should not be viewed as a defeat or a turn of the tide. While media victories are important, real victories are awaiting on the ground and inevitable Russian counter-offensive will put everything in place. General Surovikin has also reported about successful activity in Donbass and advances in this area are surely be more important.

🔷It's easier to understand the decision of the Ministry of Defense looking at a broader scale. Ukraine is currently way overstretched and depends solely on support of the West and especially the U.S. With certain Republican victory on mid-terms it is very likely that this support will be reduced no matter what happens on the ground. 

🔷In addition to that, Russian missile strikes are slowly and steadily disabling Ukrainian energy grid and if they continue at the same rate, the grid will suffer irreparable damage resulting in total blackout in a matter of weeks. This blackout would cause in total chaos and inevitable collapse of the frontline defenses.  

🔷Russian missile strikes also damage Ukrainian air defenses and ammunition storage facilities. When Ukrainian air defense falls below critical level, Russian Air Force will totally dominate Ukrainian skies without any opposition. When Ukrainian forces run out of sophisticated ammunition, they won’t be able to continue any resistance. 

🔷In view of all those weak points of Ukraine, it is indeed not reasonable to suffer heavy losses trying to hold one city despite all its importance and symbolical value.

Russia has not eliminated any American HIMARS in Ukraine, according to Reuters, quoting the Pentagon spokesman.

The fact:
The Pentagon provides no evidence for its claim, and Kiev and Washington keep confusing statements regarding the weapons being supplied to Ukraine. First, the Pentagon reports that it has no means to trace the fate of weapons being sent to Ukraine. And then a representative of the Chief Directorate of Intelligence of the Ministry of Defence of Ukraine, Vadym Skibitsky, states in an interview with the Telegraph that strikes using US multiple-launch rocket systems (HIMARS) are carried out after consultation with American side, hence the US authorities are well aware of the location of the heavy weapons. Moreover, Western journalists even film the numerous news reports footage about HIMARS. It is therefore hard to believe another statement by the Pentagon, as it has compromised its credibility through repeated lies. 

Sixteen of the declared 20 HIMARS were delivered to Ukraine. Recently, the Russian Defence Minister Sergey Shoigu reported that six launchers and over 200 HIMARS missiles had been destroyed.

​The Taiwan, China-US crisis has overshadowed Ukraine in the media field and in the people’s minds that were so much busy following the Nancy Pelosi flight.

We are living in an era in which international politics and the threat of full-fledged global war appear to laypeople to be more like fun and a computer game than a dire disaster.They are scared, but in the depth of their hearts they would love to see this happen. 

To expect China to down the jet of Nancy Pelosi was quite insane, since that would mean direct aggression against the United States. Beijing is wise enough not to hand Washington such trump cards. However, the visit itself took place despite the endless requests and warnings from China. Thus, Sino-American relations were significantly damaged. The fact that the US doesn’t respect any state’s national interests unless they match their own is common knowledge. Now it has just another proof. For the US to make this visit happen, despite the White House's attempts to disown that visit, is obviously a part of the game and a way to demonstrate the US might and to show China its place according to the US estimations and US concept of the globe. It's very unlikely that China will agree with these estimations. I can assume as well that Taiwan is becoming a kind of blackmailing instrument: Taiwan in return for abandoning the Beijing-Moscow partnership. This might be attractive to the part of the CCP establishment that is pro-US (in the sense of pro-business and pro-big money). But that is unacceptable for the opposite camp, to which belongs Xi Jinping himself, that is pro-China, pro-multipolar world and pro-independence of the country.

However, the current developments and the way Washington treats China are likely to reconcile the CCP party from within and force it to find compromises since the US moves significantly damage Chinese national pride and eloquently reveal the US approach and far-reaching plans (multiplied by the NATO expansion in Asia and NATO’s new strategic concept that defined China as a “systematic challenge” to the Alliance). And the declared intentions of the US and the signals they send about how far things might go. The key point that the whole CCP unconditionally agrees on is that: «Taiwan is China». Furthermore, it is important to bear in mind that the CCP can’t leave the current game launched by the US without a response, since in the eyes of the Chinese people this will be considered a weakness and will likely undermine their trust in the leadership. 

China has announced unprecedented military drills around Taiwan and in the Taiwanese territorial waters with missile launches that are supposed to fly through the Taiwanese airspace. Approximately 200 000 PLA military personnel have been placed on alert. 
In the case of the assault, scenario we can’t dismiss, that would be a provoked assault on Taiwan, not on Pelosi or the US. And if so, that would be a big question if the US took a risk and militarily responded to China. If they went for sanctions, the option they love the most, the consequences would be more catastrophic for the Western world and its economy than for China.

Will China take a risk and militarily restore control over Taiwan? It is hard to predict, though if it doesn’t do that now, it is unlikely that Taiwan will ever be Chinese again.

What are China’s non-military options? China might consider imposing a partial or fulscale ban on trade with Taiwan, which is majorly dependent on China, and encircling it in the ring of the blockade. At least the map of the military drills gives such a perception. 

No matter the further moves of Beijing, the US will continue playing with fire. And what is really definite is what Xi Jinping said to Biden in their latest phone call: "Those who play with fire will eventually get burned."

Then, Macron’s policy was all about preventing further social unrests. He made several openings towards the right-wing, notably adopting his separatism bill which effectively put islam under state supervision. He also kept postponing his retirement pension reforms.

We can also note how Macron adopted the "quoi qu’il en coute" policy, making the state spend a lot of money during the COVID and energy crisis, leading to France being warned by IMF to reduce spending.

Macron, during the energy crisis, went as far as to make sure ordinary people’s gas prices would stay the same during the winter, making the state pay the difference.

Now, as businesses such as bakeries are also afraid of shutting down, Macron is according to media reports getting ready to bail them out too.

Having a Western, liberal democratic leader having to spend so much time actively trying not to be overthrown is unprecedented. Macron won 2 presidential elections being first on the first ballot and winning a landslide on the runoff. Currently, according to polls, Macron’s popularity is over 40%.

Normally, democracies are kept alive by popular support and autocracies are kept alive by a mix of repression and buying people’s support. Macron’s France is increasingly becoming an exception, and a democracy whose fundamental survival tricks increasingly resembles those of an authoritarian regime. 

Obviously, as Macron made concessions, he became more popular. Macron is way more popular now than 5 years ago when he was seen as a new Hollande. But what’s the point of being popular if you can’t genuinely do your policy priorities and you must keep appeasing factions that might try to remove you from power?

Macron once said that the king’s figure was missing in French politics. That’s something a lot of French people, including normal and from the elites, believe up to a point. French people want a democracy, but at the same time wants a strong regime. 

Talking about kings, Louis XIV’s reign was always marked by the revolt, the "Fronde" that happened while he was still a child. This led Louis XIV to centralize the monarchy further , becoming the famous absolutist he was during his reign.

🇫🇷 - There is a lot of chatter in France about how "French people are sheep that never revolt". In France, having this kind of rhetoric is very common. 

Having a retirement age at 62, France is the Western state (excluding states that were East of the Iron Curtain during the cold war for the end of the discussion) that has the lowest retirement age. At retirement age of 64 as propose Macron's reform, it would still be the case.

Obviously, the reform is massively unpopular. However, Macron can afford it as he is in his second term and will be term-limited in 2027. 

LR seems to be somewhat comfortable with the reform as long as a few concessions are awarded, so it will likely succeed even if Macron's movement doesn't have a majority in parliament. 

The reason why France has and will still retain the lowest retirement age in the West? Because doing "radical" liberal economic reforms cause protests, strikes and riots and this deter governments from doing them.

🇫🇷 - Macron talks about having been elected and so he's legitimate to pass his reforms. There is some truth to his point, but he's missing one key point:

Macron was elected twice in a country where:

1) Nearly all the media supported him
2) Openly supporting the opposition candidate often lead to social ostracism
3) Cases of political violences targeting the opposition supporters were recorded.

The myth of the invincible Ukrainian army. Is the devil so scary?

Political scientist Alexei Zhivov @zhivoff especially for the channel "Soroka-Beloboka" @soroka_belaya

After the "cold shower" of the start of a special military operation, many key experts reconsidered their attitude towards the Ukrainian army and Western weapons. Previously, there was an opinion that Western weapons do not pose a serious threat, and the Ukrainian army does not exist at all.

The results "on the ground" made us take a different look at the issues raised, and many publicists rushed to the other extreme. Each tactical success of the Armed Forces of Ukraine began to be elevated to the level of "victory on the Kursk Bulge." Moreover, the Russian society began to react to the numerous stuffings from the Ukranian Center of Information and Psychological Operations, producing unfounded fears.

What about in reality? How many "overcomes" did the Armed Forces of Ukraine win, and how many did we made up by ourselves for them?

At the beginning of the special military operation, there were several tangible blows against the advancing Russian troops, which led to significant losses in people and equipment. First of all, Kharkov comes to mind. The liberation of Mariupol ended with very heavy fighting. The Armed Forces of Ukraine were able to organize resistance near Kyiv. And, perhaps, everything.

The withdrawal of Russian troops from Kyiv and from the north of Ukraine is the decision of our authorities. At the time the command arrived, the special forces were already working within the city. The Izyum offensive of the Armed Forces of Ukraine demoralized both society and the army, but the reasons were, again, domestic. Exactly the same offensives in the Kherson region bogged down, burying thousands of Ukrainian solders in the Kherson black soil. Withdrawal from the right bank of the Dnieper is also a political decision. The army successfully coped with the offensive, although it experienced a shortage of supplies.

Where did the myth about the victorious march of the Armed Forces of Ukraine come from? The Ukrainian army has indeed achieved some success, but certainly not in offensive operations. Their forte is defense, primarily urban. Our army ran into it in the Donbass. Cities in eastern Ukraine were prepared in advance for defense "to the last whole wall."

The Reich at one time defeated France with lightning speed, simply bypassing the impregnable Maginot Line from the rear. Unfortunately, the Russian army did not succeed in such a maneuver, largely due to the initial underestimation of the situation and hope for a political resolution of the issue. I think if the military operation was originally planned without regard to political instruments and inappropriate humanism, the Armed Forces of Ukraine would not have had a chance.

Most of the victories of the Ukrainian army are a direct consequence of mistakes in the planning and implementation of the operation to liberate Novorossia and Donbass. Ukraine was able to impose urban battles on the Russian army, for which our army was not ready either morally or technically. All the successes of the Armed Forces of Ukraine are associated exclusively with defensive work: the use of artillery and flexible defense, as well as a viscous fight in concrete fortified areas. We have faced a worthy adversary, but the myth about the strength and invincibility of the Ukrainian army is a delusion.

A delusion that was dispelled with the help of morally unstable Russian media with the active support of Ukrainian channels and speakers. The depression of society after the Izyum-Kherson regrouping at some point reached such intensity that people seriously believed in Ukrainian plans to attack Crimea.

In the bottom line, Ukraine was unable to return any of its regions on its own. And its maximum is to contain the smaller Russian army at the cost of colossal losses in manpower and equipment. Zelensky boasted in 2021 of creating a strong army, but now it is more like a dead army than a strong one.
